# Emily Voice Pipeline Rules

## Audio Processing Chain
Emily's voice pipeline is a multi-stage real-time system:
1. **Wake Word Detection** (openWakeWord) — always-on ONNX model listening for "Hey Emily"
2. **Voice Activity Detection** (Silero VAD v5) — adaptive noise floor, chunk-based processing
3. **Speech-to-Text** (Faster-Whisper large-v3-turbo) — CUDA float16, word-level timestamps
4. **Text-to-Speech** (CSM → Kokoro → XTTS v2) — tiered by quality/latency needs
5. **Prosody & Breath** — natural speech synthesis with emotional modulation

## Wake Word (`perception/audio/wake_word.py`)
- Use openWakeWord with custom ONNX model for "Hey Emily"
- Process audio in 80ms chunks (1280 samples @ 16kHz)
- Threshold tuning: balance false positives vs. responsiveness
- Never block the audio stream — wake word runs in parallel with VAD

## Voice Activity Detection (`perception/audio/vad.py`)
- Silero VAD v5 is the canonical VAD — never use webrtcvad or other alternatives
- Adaptive noise floor learning — track background noise and adjust threshold
- Chunk size: 512 samples (32ms @ 16kHz) for low latency
- State machine: SILENCE → SPEECH → SILENCE with hysteresis to avoid chatter
- Return speech segments with start/end timestamps for STT

## Speech-to-Text (`perception/audio/stt.py`, `streaming_stt.py`)
- Faster-Whisper large-v3-turbo is the primary STT model
- Always use CUDA with float16 precision — CPU inference is too slow
- Enable word-level timestamps and confidence scores
- Streaming STT: buffer audio until VAD detects silence, then transcribe
- Handle multilingual input if `detect_language=True` in settings
- Log low-confidence transcriptions (< 0.7) for quality monitoring

## Text-to-Speech Tier Selection (`voice/tts.py`)
Emily uses a 3-tier TTS system based on latency requirements:
- **Tier 1: CSM (Conversational Speech Model)** — ultra-low latency (< 100ms first audio), robotic quality
- **Tier 2: Kokoro** — balanced latency/quality (< 200ms first audio), natural prosody
- **Tier 3: XTTS v2** — high quality, voice cloning (< 500ms first audio), expressive

Selection logic:
- Backchannel responses ("mhm", "right") → CSM
- Normal conversation → Kokoro
- Emotional/expressive speech → XTTS v2
- User can override via settings

## Prosody Planning (`voice/prosody_planner.py`)
- Prosody parameters: pitch, rate, volume, emphasis
- Computed from `EmotionalState` (engagement, confidence, concern, enthusiasm)
- High engagement → faster rate, higher pitch variance
- Low confidence → slower rate, softer volume
- Concern → lower pitch, slower rate
- Enthusiasm → higher pitch, faster rate, more emphasis

## Breath Injection (`voice/breath_injector.py`)
- Insert natural breaths at clause boundaries (commas, periods, long pauses)
- Breath audio samples stored in `assets/breaths/`
- Frequency: every 8-12 words for natural rhythm
- Never inject breaths mid-word or in short utterances (< 5 words)

## Filler Words (`voice/filler_engine.py`)
- Inject "um", "hmm", "uh" during thinking or uncertainty
- Triggered by low LLM confidence or long generation pauses
- Filler audio samples stored in `assets/fillers/`
- Frequency: max 1 filler per 20 words to avoid sounding hesitant

## Voice Cloning (`voice/voice_clone.py`)
- XTTS v2 supports voice cloning from 6+ seconds of reference audio
- Reference audio stored in `assets/voice_profiles/<profile_name>/`
- Clone quality depends on reference audio clarity and speaker consistency
- Never clone voices without explicit user consent

## Output Streaming (`voice/output_stream.py`)
- Stream audio chunks to output device as they're generated (don't buffer entire response)
- Support interruption — user can interrupt Emily mid-sentence
- Interruption detection: VAD on input stream while TTS is active
- On interrupt: stop TTS immediately, clear buffer, switch to listening mode

## Conversation State Machine (`conversation/fsm.py`)
States: IDLE → LISTENING → PROCESSING → SPEAKING → IDLE
- **IDLE**: Wake word detection active, VAD monitoring
- **LISTENING**: User is speaking, VAD active, buffering audio
- **PROCESSING**: STT → LLM → TTS pipeline running
- **SPEAKING**: Emily is speaking, interrupt detection active
- Transitions triggered by VAD events, wake word, LLM completion, TTS completion

## Turn-Taking (`conversation/turn_detector.py`)
- Detect when user wants to speak vs. natural pause
- Use VAD silence duration + prosody cues (rising intonation = question, expect response)
- Short silence (< 500ms) → Emily continues
- Long silence (> 1.5s) → turn passes to user
- Backchannel responses don't count as full turns

## Backchannel Responses (`conversation/backchannel.py`)
- "mhm", "right", "I see", "okay" — minimal acknowledgment without taking turn
- Triggered during long user utterances to show active listening
- Frequency: every 5-8 seconds during continuous user speech
- Audio samples stored in `assets/backchannels/`
- Never interrupt user mid-word — wait for natural pause

## Interruption Handling (`conversation/interrupt_handler.py`)
- User can interrupt Emily at any time
- Detection: VAD triggers on input stream while TTS is active
- Response: immediately stop TTS, clear buffer, switch to LISTENING state
- Log interruptions for conversation flow analysis
- Don't penalize interruptions — they're natural in conversation

## Latency Budgets (from `timing/latency_budget.py`)
- Wake word detection: < 50ms per chunk
- VAD per chunk: < 1ms
- STT (Faster-Whisper): < 300ms for typical utterance
- TTS first audio byte: < 200ms (Kokoro), < 100ms (CSM)
- End-to-end voice response: < 2s (wake word → first TTS audio)

## Audio Device Management (`perception/audio/capture.py`)
- Use PyAudio for cross-platform audio I/O
- Default: 16kHz sample rate, 16-bit PCM, mono
- Buffer size: 1024 frames (64ms @ 16kHz) — balance latency vs. stability
- Handle device disconnection gracefully — log error, attempt reconnect
- Never crash on audio device errors — degrade to text-only mode

## Acoustic Echo Cancellation (`perception/audio/aec.py`)
- AEC prevents Emily from hearing her own TTS output
- Use speex or webrtc AEC library
- Reference signal: TTS output audio
- Processed signal: microphone input
- Critical for full-duplex conversation without feedback loops

## Noise Suppression (`perception/audio/noise_suppress.py`)
- RNNoise or similar ML-based noise suppression
- Apply before VAD and STT for better accuracy
- Preserve speech frequencies, attenuate background noise
- Adaptive: learn noise profile over time

## Emotion Detection (`perception/audio/emotion_detector.py`)
- Detect user emotion from speech prosody (pitch, rate, energy)
- Use pre-trained model (e.g., Wav2Vec2 fine-tuned on emotion)
- Output: valence (positive/negative), arousal (calm/excited)
- Feed into `EmotionalState` for conversation adaptation

## Speaker Identification (`perception/audio/speaker_engine.py`)
- Identify which user is speaking (multi-user households)
- Use speaker embeddings (e.g., resemblyzer, pyannote)
- Enroll users with 30+ seconds of speech samples
- Store embeddings in `users/profiles/<user_id>/speaker_embedding.npy`
- Privacy: embeddings stay local, never uploaded

## Testing Voice Pipeline
- Unit tests: mock audio streams with pre-recorded samples
- Integration tests: full pipeline with synthetic audio
- Latency tests: measure each stage with `timing/metrics.py`
- Quality tests: WER (Word Error Rate) for STT, MOS (Mean Opinion Score) for TTS
- Never test with real microphone in CI — use fixtures
